ub.com/users/chenyukang/received_events", "type": "User", "site_admin": false}], "milestone": null, "comments": 1, "created_at": "2022-10-08T10:14:18Z", "updated_at": "2022-11-06T11:23:12Z", "closed_at": "2022-11-06T11:23:12Z", "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR", "active_lock_reason": null, "body": "If I try to use \"functional record update syntax\" (aka \"struct update syntax\") with three dots instead of two, the compiler could emit a clearer error message.\n\nGiven the following code ([playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2021&gist=39a57212a40e794a2c10cfec60fdd323)):\n\n```rust\nstruct V3 {\n    x: f32,\n    y: f32,\n    z: f32\n}\n\nfn pz(v: V3) {\n    let _ = V3 {\n        z: 0.0,\n        ...v\n    };\n}\n```\n\nThe current output is:\n\n```\nerror: expected identifier, found `...`\n  --> src/lib.rs:10:9\n   |\n8  |     let _ = V3 {\n   |             -- while parsing this struct\n9  |         z: 0.0,\n10 |         ...v\n   |         ^^^ expected identifier\n\nerror[E0063]: missing fields `x` and `y` in initializer of `V3`\n --> src/lib.rs:8:13\n  |\n8 |     let _ = V3 {\n  |             ^^ missing `x` and `y`\n```\n\nIdeally the output should be more inclusive about what token was expected:\n\n```\nerror: expected identifier or `..`, found `...`\n```\n\nand include a suggestion directing the programmer to the correct syntax:\n\n```\nhelp: to fill in the rest of the fields from `v`, write `..v` (note only two dots)\n```\n\n**Motivation**\n\n* Programmers who also write in JavaScript might be familiar with the similar [spread syntax in object literals](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/Spread_syntax#spread_in_object_literals), which uses `...`\n* In English prose, `...` is more common than `..`\n\n<!-- TRIAGEBOT_START -->\n\n<!-- TRIAGEBOT_ASSIGN_START -->\n\n<!-- TRIAGEBOT_ASSIGN_DATA_START$${\"user\":\"chenyukang\"}$$TRIAGEBOT_ASSIGN_DATA_END -->\n\n<!-- TRIAGEBOT_ASSIGN_END -->\n